WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.700
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. This is one&nbsp;
of a series of videos on the foundations of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:14.700 --> 00:00:20.490
mathematics. Up till now, we've been talking&nbsp;
about arithmetic. Now we are going to enter&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:20.490 --> 00:00:27.480
a new phase when we talk about the foundations&nbsp;
of geometry. Geometry is probably the biggest&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:27.480 --> 00:00:34.050
subject in mathematics. It's historically&nbsp;
a very interesting and rich subject and one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:34.050 --> 00:00:41.190
whose foundations are notoriously difficult to&nbsp;
establish. One of the challenges with geometry&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:41.190 --> 00:00:47.550
is that there are so many concepts from it which&nbsp;
are so familiar already to us in our daily life,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:47.550 --> 00:00:55.800
words that already have a pre-assigned meaning to&nbsp;
us from experience. So one of the challenges is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:55.800 --> 00:01:06.060
to come up with definitions, proper definitions&nbsp;
of many terms, such as what is a point, line,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:06.060 --> 00:01:19.440
plane, circle, triangle, square, continuum,&nbsp;
space, cube, curve, surface, distance, angle,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:20.970 --> 00:01:29.880
parallel, perpendicular, congruent, similar,&nbsp;
between, larger, smaller, straight, reflection,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:29.880 --> 00:01:39.870
rotation, translation, sphere, ellipse, conic,&nbsp;
ray, hemisphere, cone, area, volume. I probably&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:39.870 --> 00:01:45.060
could go on with a few more pages of terms&nbsp;
that are generally quite familiar to most&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:45.060 --> 00:01:55.440
people but need precise mathematical definitions&nbsp;
in order for geometry to make sense. In this list,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:55.440 --> 00:02:01.350
there are some that are much harder to establish&nbsp;
than others, and I've indicated those especially&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:01.350 --> 00:02:11.080
hard ones with some underlines in red. Distance&nbsp;
is a problematic concept to take down concretely.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:11.080 --> 00:02:18.130
Angle is even more problematic and even more&nbsp;
difficult, as is the notion of curve and surface.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:18.130 --> 00:02:24.070
All of these are quite hard, in fact, and involve&nbsp;
a lot of advanced mathematics if you're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:24.070 --> 00:02:31.270
do them properly. And there's one term here which&nbsp;
is very, very difficult to establish correctly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:31.270 --> 00:02:38.050
and that is the notion of the continuum. What do&nbsp;
we mean exactly by a straight line or continuum of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:38.050 --> 00:02:43.780
points? We would have to say a lot about that&nbsp;
and about the difficulties involved in that.

00:02:43.780 --> 00:02:52.030
So let's now go from the words to some pictures&nbsp;
and show how you get the meanings of these words&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:52.030 --> 00:02:59.920
from being shown lots of pictures in everyday&nbsp;
life. We learn the meanings of words by being&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:59.920 --> 00:03:07.690
shown lots of examples; we rarely get official&nbsp;
formal definitions of things. So for example, to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:07.690 --> 00:03:12.460
learn what a point is, we've all been shown lots&nbsp;
of points, and after you see a number of them,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:12.460 --> 00:03:18.010
you should get the idea of what a point is. This&nbsp;
particular configuration of points, of course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:18.010 --> 00:03:23.200
corresponds to stars, which is something that's&nbsp;
very important historically in terms of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:23.200 --> 00:03:30.700
interests of our ancestors. Here are some examples&nbsp;
of lines. There's a circle, there are some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:30.700 --> 00:03:36.100
squares, there's another square. The orientation&nbsp;
of the square is not so crucial; it doesn't matter&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:36.100 --> 00:03:42.760
how you rotate it, it's still a square. Here are&nbsp;
examples of triangles illustrating that there are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:42.760 --> 00:03:47.140
different possible approaches. Here we have a&nbsp;
triangle defined in terms of three lines, here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:47.140 --> 00:03:55.990
in terms of three points and three lines, here in&nbsp;
terms more of the area enclosed. Here are parallel&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.990 --> 00:04:01.300
lines. You can just see them; you look at them,&nbsp;
you see sort of what the idea is. Here a notion&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:01.300 --> 00:04:06.550
of perpendicular; if you see enough of them, you&nbsp;
get the idea of perpendicular without being told&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:06.550 --> 00:04:14.890
precisely what it means. The problem with all this&nbsp;
is that pictures don't replace proper definitions.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.890 --> 00:04:23.350
When we come to do proofs, we need more precise&nbsp;
definitions to base everything on. That's going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:23.350 --> 00:04:29.980
to be a very big challenge: replacing intuitive&nbsp;
everyday understandings of things with formal,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:29.980 --> 00:04:36.760
precise mathematical definitions. And another&nbsp;
question related is how does one specify&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:36.760 --> 00:04:43.420
geometric objects? For example, let's say I take&nbsp;
this triangle here, and I want to pass on the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:43.420 --> 00:04:50.080
information about this triangle to you. If I can't&nbsp;
show you a picture, suppose I have to write you a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.080 --> 00:04:55.780
letter or an email, and I want to express this&nbsp;
triangle. How do I do it efficiently? In other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:55.780 --> 00:05:01.330
words, what kind of information is required&nbsp;
to specify a geometrical object? That's going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:01.330 --> 00:05:06.190
to be an important question because it's very&nbsp;
directly connected with the idea of a definition.

00:05:06.190 --> 00:05:16.300
This general approach of pictures on an empty&nbsp;
page is not one that we are going to pursue all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:16.300 --> 00:05:21.370
that much. We are going to look at a rather&nbsp;
more structured approach to geometry which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:21.370 --> 00:05:28.000
makes definitions much simpler to frame. In&nbsp;
our approach to the foundations of geometry,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:33.550
we're going to rely a lot on a fabulous&nbsp;
technological innovation of modern times,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:33.550 --> 00:05:41.830
namely a sheet of graph paper. A sheet of&nbsp;
graph paper is indispensable for school&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:41.830 --> 00:05:47.710
work in geometry. That's going to be a point I'm&nbsp;
going to emphasize over and over again. And it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:47.710 --> 00:05:55.000
also indispensable for setting up definitions in&nbsp;
geometry and connecting to a lot of the modern&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:05.290
digital world. So here's a piece of graph paper:&nbsp;
lines horizontal and vertical, and on it, we can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:05.290 --> 00:06:12.520
illustrate many geometrical concepts. For example,&nbsp;
a point can now be specified by its coordinates,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:12.520 --> 00:06:18.940
in this case, for this point, 10, 3. And so we can&nbsp;
end up defining points in terms of coordinates,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:18.940 --> 00:06:25.330
which is something that we're going to do. If&nbsp;
we look at a line, a line can now be defined&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:25.330 --> 00:06:31.690
in terms of the pattern of the points that are on&nbsp;
it. For example, this line here is determined by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:31.690 --> 00:06:38.050
the fact that we're going over one, up two to&nbsp;
go from point to point on it. We can make the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:38.050 --> 00:06:44.410
notion of perpendicularity and parallelism much&nbsp;
clearer by the use of coordinates. This line is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:44.410 --> 00:06:50.320
parallel to this one because this one also goes&nbsp;
over one and up two from step to step. And this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:50.320 --> 00:06:56.230
line and this line are perpendicular because&nbsp;
the one over and two up here are balanced with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:56.230 --> 00:07:05.380
a one up and two over for this line. So this is&nbsp;
a framework that ties down the plane very rigidly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:05.380 --> 00:07:09.490
and makes sure that we are really working on a&nbsp;
plane and not rather on the surface of a sphere&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:09.490 --> 00:07:17.140
or some other curved surface. It's a great aid&nbsp;
for connecting arithmetic and geometry. It allows&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:17.140 --> 00:07:24.910
us accurate specification of geometrical objects.&nbsp;
It naturally applies to the world of graphics and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:24.910 --> 00:07:32.590
digital design, and it's an accurate basis for&nbsp;
measurement and gives us natural definitions.

00:07:32.590 --> 00:07:40.420
So now, with that general introduction, we need&nbsp;
to get a little bit more specific. We're going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:40.420 --> 00:07:47.560
to have to go back in time to history, to the&nbsp;
most important mathematical book ever written,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:47.560 --> 00:07:53.200
that's Euclid's Elements. Every treatment&nbsp;
of geometry, whether ancient or modern,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:53.200 --> 00:07:59.530
must start with an understanding of Euclid's&nbsp;
accomplishments and some of his difficulties.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:59.530 --> 00:08:04.630
That's what we're gonna do next time. I hope&nbsp;
you're gonna join me. I'm Norman Wildberger.

